<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33833" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole littoralis Cole" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole littoralis Cole" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="littoralis">littoralis</taxonomicName>
foveate, and in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33868" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole micula Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole micula Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micula">micula</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142583" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soritis">soritis</taxonomicName>
carinulate); postpetiole from above diamond-shaped, trapezoidal, or spinose. Minor: eye medium-sized to large.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="598">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142583" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soritis">P. soritis</taxonomicName>
is distinguished within this complex by the following combination of traits.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="598">Major: extensive transverse carinulae of occiput curve laterally and forward, with many reaching the anterior border of the head capsule; almost entire dorsal surface of head, including clypeus, carinulate; rugulae lacking on head; humerus low and smoothly convex; postpetiole seen from above laterally angulate; small denticle present on anterior ventral surface of postpetiole in side view.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="599">Minor: dorsal profile of promesonotum lined solely with evenly spaced pairs of clavate hairs; similar hairs occur on the waist; eye very large.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="599">
The tangled infraspecific nomenclature of this species has been built mostly on variation in the sculpturing of the minor's head. From central Texas north and west, the posterior dorsal surface is foveolate and opaque (
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:151179" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole pilifera subsp. rufescens" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole arnoldi rufescens Arnold" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pilifera" subSpecies="rufescens">subsp. rufescens</taxonomicName>
= 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:232344" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole pilifera subsp. campestris" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole sitarches campestris Creighton" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pilifera" subSpecies="campestris">subsp. campestris</taxonomicName>
). To the south, into Mexico, it is smooth and shiny, as illustrated here (
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34013" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole pilifera subsp. sitarches" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole sitarches Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pilifera" subSpecies="sitarches">subsp. sitarches</taxonomicName>
). Westward to Arizona and Utah it is carinulate (typical 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142583" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soritis">soritis</taxonomicName>
). Whether this variation is truly geographic within a single species or reflects the existence of sibling species around 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34013" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole sitarches Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole sitarches Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sitarches">sitarches</taxonomicName>
sensu str., is a question that awaits closer field and museum research.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="599">
Measurements (mm) Lectotype 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142583" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soritis">soritis major</taxonomicName>
: HW 1.16, HL 1.22, SL 0.60, EL 0.20, PW 0.52.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="599">
Syntype 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34013" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole sitarches Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole sitarches Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sitarches">sitarches minor</taxonomicName>
(no type 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142583" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soritis">soritis</taxonomicName>
minors available): HW 0.46, HL 0.50, SL 0.48, EL 0.12, PW 0.30.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="599">Color Major: head and appendages light reddish brown, body a slightly contrasting medium reddish brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="599">Minor: body plain light brown, appendages brownish yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="599">Range Mississippi west to Colorado, Texas, Arizona, and northern Mexico.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="599">
Biology In eastern Colorado, Gregg (1963) found 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142583" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soritis">P. soritis</taxonomicName>
under rocks in the clay soil of cottonwood-willow woodland and shortgrass prairie, from 1000 to 1300 m. I encountered it near Datil, New Mexico, in open juniper woodland (Wilson 1957c). A nuptial flight was observed in progress following rainfall on 9 August in an abandoned homesite clearing. The swarms of flying ants, which held resolutely to the clearings, consisted mostly of males. The aggregations were roughly circular in shape and hovered from about half a meter to nearly 2 meters above the surface, depending on wind conditions. Winged queens flew into the swarms and were quickly seized by a male, whereupon the pair spiraled to the ground together. After insemination, the queens shed their wings and ran off over the ground, evidently in search of a nest site.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
